To nurture virtue in a corrupt society, yet hide one's own virtue;
To educate the people in a chaotic nation, and care for one's own town;
To teach as a master in seclusion, and wander as a scholar in the countryside;
To herd the common folk, and if one uses machinery in the forest, it will destroy the wilderness;
To call one's name a commitment to righteousness, and make friends in the wilderness;
To fix one's gaze on the stars, and establish order at the social gates.
A virtuous person is the source of all accomplishments.
The king studies righteousness at the side of the Way.

When virtue is hidden in a corrupt society, it is like trying to keep clear water in a muddy pool. The master nurtures his own virtue while caring for the people in his own town. He teaches as a master in seclusion and wanders as a scholar in the countryside. He herds the common folk, and if he uses machinery in the forest, it will destroy the wilderness. He calls his name a commitment to righteousness and makes friends in the wilderness. He fixes his gaze on the stars and establishes order at the social gates. A virtuous person is the source of all accomplishments. The king studies righteousness at the side of the Way.

This passage highlights the importance of virtue in society and the role of the individual in cultivating it, even in difficult circumstances. The master, despite living in a corrupt and chaotic nation, focuses on educating the people in his own town and nurturing his own virtue. He teaches as a master in seclusion, away from the distractions of the marketplace, and wanders as a scholar in the countryside, connecting with nature and gaining wisdom. He herds the common folk, using his leadership to guide and protect them, and avoids using machinery in the forest, recognizing the importance of preserving the natural world. He calls his name a commitment to righteousness, building relationships based on shared values, and fixes his gaze on the stars, looking to the cosmos for guidance and inspiration. Ultimately, the virtuous person is the source of all accomplishments, and the king studies righteousness at the side of the Way, modeling virtuous leadership for his people.
